    <p>
        To find the square root of a fraction, work out the square root of the numerator and square root of the denominator separately.
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the square root of <m>\frac{36}{400}</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To find the square root of <m>\frac{36}{400}</m>, take the square root of numerator and denominator separately.
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    \sqrt{\frac{36}{400}} = \frac{\sqrt{36}}{\sqrt{400}}
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                Express the numerator and denominator in terms of its prime factor pairs.
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    \frac{\sqrt{36}}{\sqrt{400}} = \frac{\sqrt{{\color{blue}2} \times {\color{blue}2} \times {\color{red} 3} \times {\color{red}3}}}{\sqrt{{\color{blue}2} \times {\color{blue}2} \times {\color{red}2} \times {\color{red}2} \times 5 \times 5}}
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                Take one factor from each pair, and multiply.
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \frac{{\color{blue}2}}{{\color{blue}2} \times {\color{red}2} \times 5} \amp = \frac{6}{20}</mrow>
                    <mrow></mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{6}{20} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Work out: <m>\sqrt{28\frac{4}{9}}</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To find the <m>\sqrt{28\frac{4}{9}}</m>, first convert <m>28\frac{4}{9}</m> into improper fraction.
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    28 \frac{4}{9} = \frac{(9 \times 28)+4}{9} = \frac{256}{9}
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                Now, <m>\sqrt{28\frac{4}{9}} = \sqrt{\frac{256}{9}} = \frac{\sqrt{256}}{\sqrt{9}}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Express the numerator and denominator in terms of its prime factor pairs.
            </p><p>
                <me>
                    \frac{\sqrt{256}}{\sqrt{9}} = \frac{\sqrt{{\color{blue} 2} \times {\color{blue} 2} \times {\color{red} 2} \times {\color{red} 2} \times {\color{green} 2} \times {\color{green} 2} \times 2 \times 2 }}{\sqrt{{\color{blue}3} \times {\color{blue}3}}}
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                Take one factor from each pair, and multiply.
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \frac{{\color{blue} 2} \times {\color{red} 2} \times {\color{green} 2} \times 2}{{\color{blue}3} }  \amp  = \frac{16}{3}</mrow>
                    <mrow></mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{16}{3}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
